label.value: Positive Bartonella henselae nucleic acid test in the blood circulation

definition.value: Detection of nucleic acid of Bartonella henselae in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

label.value: Positive Dengue virus PCR test in the blood circulation
Positive CSF JC-virus nucleic acid test

definition.value: Detection of JC-virus nucleic acid in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

label.value: Positive bloodstream plasmodium falciparum nucleic acid pathogen test

definition.value: Detection of nucleic acid of Plasmodium falciparum (a type of Malaria parasite) in the blood circulation by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

label.value: Elevated red cell pyruvate kinase activity

definition.value: Activity or concentration of pyruvate kinase (EC 2.7.1.40) in erythrocytes above the upper limit of normal. Pyruvate kinase (EC 2.7.1.40) is a glycolytic enzyme that catalyzes the transphosphorylation from phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) to ADP, yielding pyruvate and ATP.

label.value: Reduced sepiapterin reductase activity in cultured fibroblasts
Elevated circulating vasoactive intestinal peptide concentration

definition.value: The concentration of oxalate in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the oropharynx positive. The oropharynx is defined as the middle part of the throat and includes the soft palate, the side and back walls of the throat, the tonsils, and the posterior one-third of the tongue.

label.value: Positive oropharynx poliovirus nucleic acid test

definition.value: Detection of poliovirus nucleic acid in the oropharynx by a method such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR) or reverse transcriptase (RT)-PCR.

label.value: Positive synonvial fluid infectious agent test

definition.value: Any kind of test for an infectious agent in the synovial fluid (i.e., in a joint) positive.
Growth of an infectious agent in a culture derived from synovial fluid.
The presence of antibodies in the blood circulation that react against a component of parvovirus.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in muscle tissue.
An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in a bone.
A lipoma that is localized to the spine.

An anomalous configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins without passing through the capillaries and that is located in adjacent to the spine, i.e., in a location that is normally occupied by muscles, ligaments, nerves, and other tissues that run alongside the spinal column.

A closed sac that has developed in the upper jaw bone (maxilla) and contains fluid or semi-solid material. Cystic lesions of the maxilla are benign entities with both odontogenic and non-odontogenic origins.
A closed sac that has developed in the lower jaw bone (mandibula) and contains fluid or semi-solid material.
Underdevelopment of the third cranial nerve (oculomotor nerve).
The amount of 2-oxoisocaproic in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
